prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Chemical Study of the High-Mass Star Forming Clumps in W33

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
We propose to observe the six clumps W33Main1, W33A1, W33B1, W33B, W33A, and W33Main with ALMA in most compact configuration. At the proposed frequency, this yields a synthesized beam size of 1.3". However, to be comparable with our SMA observations we plan to smooth the data to a lower resolution of ~3". Since for our settings the lowest angular resolution possible in the OT is 2.5", we calculated the desired sensitivity and the expected source properties for this beam.
The frequency range of 278-282 and 290-294 GHz is chosen to cover the same range as our previous APEX observations of these clumps. Since the line widths of the transitions detected in the APEX data are larger than 2 km/s, a spectral resolution of 1.2 km/s (smaller than the spectral resolution of our APEX data) is sufficient to resolve the spectral lines. To increase the sensitivity, we chose the dual polarization products.
To observe extended emission in the six clumps, we want to cover them with customized mosaics. Due to the restrictions of 150 pointings per science goal, we divided this number equally over the six sources to cover an area as large as possible per clump. At the proposed frequency range, the field of view of ALMA is 22". The customized mosaics consist of 19 pointings per source and have a hexagonal shape, covering an area of ~1 arcmin^2. The separation between pointings is half a beam to achieve Nyquist sampling. To also cover dust emission in the north and west of the central continuum peak in W33 Main, as seen in our SMA observations, we increased the hexagonal mosaic of W33 Main, consisting of 37 pointings and covering an area of ~1.7 arcmin^2. The total number of pointings for this science goal is thus 132 pointings. Comparing the area of these mosaics with our SMA observations, we conclude that they will cover the extended line emission in our ALMA data.
The expected source properties are estimated from the weakest lines in our APEX observations (per source) which have peak flux densities of 2.4 – 5.2 Jy in the 24" APEX beam. Our SMA observations showed that the dust cores cover areas of ~10"x~10" and that the line emission is similarly extended. Thus, assuming that the line emission of the ALMA observations will be confined to an area of 10"x10", we estimated that the weakest lines will be stronger than 0.17 – 0.37 Jy in a 2.5" beam in all sources.
The advantage of ALMA over other interferometers with comparable spatial resolution is that a much higher sensitivity can be reached in a much shorter observing time with a much better uv-coverage. Although similar observations could be conducted with the SMA in justifiable time (~1-2 tracks), the uv-coverage would be much worse compared to the ALMA observations. Since we expect the line emission to be clumpy, accumulating in complex structures, we need a good uv-coverage, as provided by ALMA, to recover also the more complex structures. Since our APEX observations will provide the zero-spacing information for the proposed ALMA project, observations with the ACA are not necessary and we set the largest angular scale to a value that is still covered by the 12m array.
The 10s per pointing that are mandatory give us a sensitivity of 36 mJy per pointing for a 2.5" beam and the finest spectral resolution of our data. This sensitivity yields a SNR of 4.7, high enough to detect even the weakest lines in our APEX data. Thus, we do not ask for a higher observing time per pointing. In total, we request an observing time of 1 h.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract:
The W33 complex is an ideal object to study the chemical evolution of molecular gas along an evolutionary sequence since it contains typical star forming regions in various stages of formation. Previous observations with the APEX telescope and the SMA have shown that the chemical composition of the molecular gas changes dramatically along the evolutionary sequence, especially on smaller scales. Since the APEX and SMA spectra have been observed in different frequency ranges, our observations did not allow a quantitative comparison of the obtained results on small and large scales.
We propose ALMA observations of the six W33 clumps at 278-282 and 290-294 GHz to cover the same frequency range as our APEX observations and thus trace the emission of the same transitions of the same molecules to smaller scales. To be comparable to our SMA data, the observations are proposed for the most compact configuration. The ALMA observations will complement our previous chemical studies with the SMA and the APEX telescope, allowing us to study the chemical evolution of the molecular gas on smaller scales in greater detail in all six star-forming clumps.
